title: For Sale/Trade:  Sig Sauer P226 .40
postcontent: Sig Sauer P226 with rail in .40 S & W and factory DAK trigger. Excellent shape with original box, Hogue grip, Serpa Holster, Sig Nite Sights and 2 magazines. Firm on Price - onpen to trades but it has to be something I can't live without. Update - don't ask my bottom dollar - I won't respond - "firm" should tell you what you need to know. I will be going through Wausau and Eau Claire on Monday, April 11For those not familar with the DAK trigger, here is the description:DAK-(for Double Action Kellerman, after the designer of the system). When firing the pistol the first trigger pull is only 6.5 lbf (compared to 12 lbf for the standard DAO). After the pistol fires and the trigger is released forward the trigger has an intermediate reset point that is approximately halfway to the trigger at rest position. The trigger pull from this intermediate reset point is 8.5 lbf. If the trigger is released all the way forward, this will engage the primary trigger reset and have a trigger pull of 6.5 lbf. To engage the intermediate reset the trigger must be held to the rear while the slide is cycled, either manually or by the recoil of a round being fired.In bare-bones description, the DAK mechanism provides a hammer-fired full-length double-action trigger pull, with complete repeat-strike capability, that is notably lighter than other full-length DAO pull mechanisms. Developed by the engineers at Sauer in Germany, the new DAK trigger system delivers a smooth, consistent 6.5-pound full-length trigger pull that is much closer to the weight of a Glock than any conventional DAO but also has complete restrike capability without any pretensioning or prestressing of the internal firing mechanism. There is nothing magical about the design; everything is accomplished by simple mechanical advantages in the trigger/hammer linkages. The key is that the engineers were able to extend the "leverage arm" of the hammer from the pivot point (like sitting farther from the fulcrum of a seesaw) so that less force is required from the trigger while remaining within the existing dimensions of the P226 and P229 frames. Externally, the only visible difference between a SIG DAK mechanism and a conventional SIG DAO mechanism is that the DAK trigger has a slightly slimmer profile and the DAK hammer sits completely within the frame when at rest, while the DAO hammer protrudes slightly. Other attractive features include the fact that the slide must be locked back and the magazine removed to disassemble, and it can be disassembled without having to pull the trigger.

title: For Sale:  1900 Colt Liightning w/Factory Letter
postcontent: The Colt M1877 is a double action revolver manufactured by Colt's Patent Fire Arms from January 1877 to 1909 for a total of 166,849 revolvers. The Model 1877 was offered in three calibers, which lent them three unofficial names: the "Lightning", the "Thunderer", and the "Rainmaker". The principal difference between the models was the cartridge in which they were chambered: the "Lightning" being chambered in .38 Long Colt "Thunderer" in .41 Colt. Both models had a six-round ammunition capacity. An earlier model in .32 Colt known as the "Rainmaker" was offered in 1877. The one offered here is a Colt Double Action Lightning .38 cal Revolver Model of 1877 with a 3 ½” barrel. Serial number: 118168 manufactured in 1900. Original Colt letter included confirming serial number, Caliber, Barrel Length, and blue finish. Stocks not listed but are original to the gun. Traces of blue along with Patina fading to brown. Action is tight and works, as it should. Please view all pictures and ask questions if necessary. If you hold a Curios and Relics licensee I can ship direct to you if not will go to your FFL. The Holographic Hybrid Sight I (HHS I) features an EXPS3 with a G33 magnifier. It has great utility for any shooter, whose target ranges vary from close to mid-range. The HHS I provides a solution for engaging threats in close-quarter combat situations, then quickly transitions to a 600-meter targeting or surveillance situation. A quick switch-to-side (STS) mount offers simple, fast disengagement of the G33 magnifier. 
EOTech is one of the most trusted manufacturer of military and civilian weapon sights and accessories, and the HHS I is the perfect example of why. The HHS I combines the popular EXPS3 with the innovative G33 3X magnifier and Switch-To-Side mount. Both of these units work seamlessly together and offer quick-detach, locking mounts. The EXPS3 is among the most compact units available requiring minimal rail mounting space. When combined with the G33 magnifier the entire HHS I units measure a mere 8.1" and requires only 2.75" of rail space for mounting. When faced with variable situations the HHS I is the ideal choice with the ability to quickly switch from 1x to 3x with the flip of a finger. The G33 is held in place with a strong detent that maintains its perfect alignment with the EXPS3, and hold the unit out of the operator's way in CQB situations. Perfect for any situation, the HHS I offers 20 illumination intensities, anti-glare coatings with high light gathering capability, true holographic transmission for a parallax free optic that features a true heads-up display for shooting with both eyes open. Additional features of the HH I are Night vision compatibility as well as a ballistic BDC reticle matched to .223 ammunition.  This sight kit was sent to EOTech for all recall updated.
